<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-697-832  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 697 832.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InTech  July 1990 v37 n7 p23(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Engineering for maintenance: look at the long term.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ludwig, Steven W.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Technicians and electricians must be involved in the design of anautomation system from the start to help ensure themaintainability of the system.andP;  The long-term cost-effectivenessof a system is affected by the ability of the system to remain inservice with only regular maintenance and minimum downtime.andO;Ensuring maintainability requires assessment of equipment access,spare parts inventories, standardization, training on newequipment, suitable test equipment and calibration of equipment.andO;Design engineers' evaluations must be tied to customersatisfaction.andP;  Other critical areas include quality ofdocumentation, designing for easy replacement, minimizingnecessary equipment, and making sure that training and spare partsare adequate.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MaintainabilityMaintenanceEngineeringRequirements AnalysisPlanningAutomationGoals and ObjectivesTutorial.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>